<BaseLayout
  title="research — christopher joy"
  description="Research, working papers, and policy briefs by Christopher J. Joy."
>
  <div class="page-header">
    <h1>Research &amp; Writing</h1>
  </div>
  <hr class="rule-accent" />

  <p>
    I work primarily with Stata and R for data and statistical analysis, with experience
    using large datasets and building databases. My research sits at the intersection of
    political economy, development economics, and Southeast Asian studies.
  </p>

  <ul class="research-list">
    <li>
      <span class="research-tag">Working Paper</span>
      <span class="research-title">The Embedded State and Vietnam's COVID-19 Response</span>
      <p class="research-desc">
        The paper argues Vietnam's ruling party's embedded state capacity marshalled political
        mobilization while altering dynamics of state-society relations — a retrenchment of
        earlier marketisation of life — to contain COVID-19's spread.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="research-tag">Working Paper</span>
      <span class="research-title">Found Women: Economic Development and Female Empowerment in Southeast Asia</span>
      <p class="research-desc">
        Against the backdrop of the world's "missing women", Southeast Asia offers an example
        of both developed and developing countries that do not see unnatural sex-birth imbalance,
        raising the question: what is the state of female empowerment and economic development
        in Southeast Asia/ASEAN?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="research-tag">Article</span>
      <span class="research-title">Private Equity, The Enabling State and The Logics of Infrastructure Investment</span>
      <p class="research-desc">
        Using England's water infrastructure as a lens, the article argues that the early
        reverberations of privatisation, alongside enabling states, empowered large pools of
        private equity capital to rearrange asset logics and invest in public infrastructure.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="research-tag">Policy Brief</span>
      <span class="research-title">Extra-welfarism: Welfare Economics and The Expanded Childhood Tax Credit</span>
      <p class="research-desc">
        A policy brief on the US expanded Child Tax Credit as part of the American Rescue Plan
        Act of 2021, discussed in the context of welfare economics and extra-welfarism.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="research-tag">Policy Brief</span>
      <span class="research-title">Nusantara: Ibukota Baru or Ghost Town?</span>
      <p class="research-desc">
        A policy brief on Indonesia's new capital city, Nusantara. Discusses the political
        economy of the move, environmental concerns, and the economic rationale behind the
        relocation from Jakarta.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="research-tag">In Progress</span>
      <span class="research-title">Viet Nam and US Tariffs</span>
      <p class="research-desc">
        An ongoing project examining the effects of shifting US trade policy on Viet Nam's
        export-oriented economy.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</BaseLayout>
